## Quantitative Impacts and Economic Costs of Pollution

While exact global figures vary, the economic costs of pollution are substantial. For example, air pollution alone is estimated to cause millions of premature deaths annually, with associated healthcare costs and lost labor productivity reaching hundreds of billions of dollars worldwide. The World Health Organization estimates that ambient air pollution causes 4.2 million deaths per year globally, imposing significant economic burdens on health systems and economies ([Khan Academy, 2023](https://www.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/microeconomics/market-failure-and-the-role-of-government/environmental-regulation/a/the-economics-of-pollution-cnx)).

### Case Study: Chemical Pollution in England

In 2010, a chemical firm in southeast England discharged waste into a lake, causing environmental damage and reducing fish populations. The firm prioritized profit over environmental protection, polluting the lake without incurring costs for the damage inflicted on anglers and local communities. This case illustrates how the lack of a pollution market allows firms to externalize costs, resulting in market failure ([UKEssays, 2018](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/economics/pollution-leads-to-market-failure-economics-essay.php)).

