## Economic Theories and Frameworks Addressing Pollution

### Coase Theorem and Market-Based Solutions

The Coase theorem suggests that if property rights are well-defined and transaction costs are low, private bargaining can resolve externalities like pollution. However, in reality, high transaction costs and diffuse pollution impacts make such bargaining impractical on a large scale. This limitation reinforces the need for government intervention or market-based instruments such as pollution taxes or tradable emission permits to internalize external costs ([Institute for Energy Research, 2023](https://www.instituteforenergyresearch.org/fossil-fuels/coal/air-pollution-and-alleged-market-failures/)).

### Command-and-Control vs. Market-Based Instruments

Traditional environmental policies have relied on command-and-control approaches, mandating specific pollution control technologies or emission limits. While effective in some cases, these approaches can be inflexible and costly. Market-based instruments, such as pollution taxes and cap-and-trade systems, offer more cost-effective solutions by providing economic incentives for pollution reduction and innovation ([GraduateWay, 2020](https://graduateway.com/market-failure-in-environmental-pollution-and-the-attempts-to-extend-the-market/)).

