## Implications for Global Economic Systems

### Global Scale of Market Failure

Pollution transcends national boundaries, making it a global market failure. The atmosphere, oceans, and other environmental commons are shared resources, and pollution in one region can have widespread effects. Without coordinated international policies and mechanisms to internalize global externalities, markets alone cannot efficiently allocate resources to address pollution ([Khan Academy, 2023](https://www.khanacademy.org/economics-finance-domain/microeconomics/market-failure-and-the-role-of-government/environmental-regulation/a/the-economics-of-pollution-cnx)).

### Economic Growth vs. Environmental Quality Trade-Off

Economic production often involves trade-offs between growth and environmental quality. While production increases welfare by providing goods and services, it also generates pollution that harms health and ecosystems. Balancing these trade-offs requires recognizing pollution as a market failure and implementing policies that align private incentives with social welfare ([MBA Knowledge Base, 2023](https://www.mbaknol.com/managerial-economics/the-economists-view-of-environmental-pollution/)).

